49:00.400 --> 49:06.400
And if people are interested, then it's kind of a matchmaking type of thing as I see it somehow, you know.

49:07.400 --> 49:18.400
Right. My sense is that the dynamics would make the councils fairly conservative in their approaches and that you probably they probably tend to not.

49:18.400 --> 49:24.400
It would seem to discourage that and which, you know, which may be fine.

49:24.400 --> 49:51.400
You know, I think that a lot of this idea of the new in terms of product is a product of capitalism and really not where development and communism development in communism is likely to likely to appear to us as as immaterial in many respects and resources, you know, dedicated towards forms of development that don't even register as, you know, you know, shiny new products and things like that, which is how capitalism treats development.

49:51.400 --> 50:00.400
But so, yeah, I think that, you know, we we it would it would likely be very different.

50:00.400 --> 50:15.400
Something I really like is is I've been reading a lot of Amadeo Bordiga, who has quite who who is useful because this way of thinking about communism is so radically different and it shines such a different light on the planning literature.

50:16.400 --> 50:43.400
But a point that he makes is that if, as many planners say, that there would be no discounting of time preference, right, that there would be no discounting of of, you know, wealth so that the value of something for future generations would be treated the same as today, that we would we would be much, much, much more conservative with fixed capital.

50:43.400 --> 50:55.400
Right. And that, you know, capitalism requires us to to waste fixed capital and infrastructure, right, because producers have to run the machines faster in order to get as much stuff out of it.

50:55.400 --> 51:10.400
But in fact, the dynamics of the dynamics of a future society would almost be like kind of worshiping fixed capital, like the Roman aqueducts that last for thousands of years in a way of just treating these things as these incredible kind of organic parts of our society.

51:10.400 --> 51:23.400
So I think that that would just lead to a very different, you know, attitude if we really saw how valuable these things are and didn't, you know, and didn't discount the future and sort of ravage the planet.

51:23.400 --> 51:29.400
Our whole idea of what is valuable and what isn't would just transform so much.

51:30.400 --> 51:36.400
And this kind of hints towards something that you briefly mentioned, which is the question of laws of motion.

51:36.400 --> 51:46.400
And you said that what Saros describes are not really like fundamentally different laws of motions, which kind of implies that you have something different in mind.

51:46.400 --> 52:02.400
And I'm absolutely in favor, I have to say, of a maximalist approach with regards to the question of planning and political economy, meaning that I believe we need to aim for the development of fundamentally different types of laws of motion.

52:03.400 --> 52:10.400
