52:10.400 --> 52:25.400
But when you get to the end, more or less painting a picture of what a planner key could look like, you do not really try to describe the fundamentals of these new or different types of laws of motion.

52:25.400 --> 52:43.400
And I'm not sure whether this is an ongoing project or if this is inherent in your radically procedural idea of how a transformation would come about and what actually a conception of communism would look like.

52:43.400 --> 52:51.400
It is that, and it is the impossibility of describing communism as a state rather than a process.

52:51.400 --> 53:00.400
And I think that, you know, communism, as I imagine it, will appear from the very first moment of the revolution.

53:00.400 --> 53:08.400
It will spread by creating itself, but it will still nonetheless need to go through a period of transition where it stabilizes.

53:08.400 --> 53:25.400
So revolution immediately produces some form of communist production by say, you know, making wage labor voluntary and organizing things on the basis of free association.

53:25.400 --> 53:33.400
But that process has to stabilize, it has to spread, it has to strengthen itself and become resilient.

53:33.400 --> 53:41.400
And so what communism looks like in the beginning in year 10 is probably nothing like it looks like in year 100.

53:41.400 --> 53:50.400
And I can say almost nothing about year 100 because I don't actually think that there are any laws of motion for communism.

53:50.400 --> 54:00.400
I think that this is where actually I would critique Marx, who thinks that there is a kind of trans-historical law of motion.

54:00.400 --> 54:18.400
And in many places he indicates that labor saving innovation and reduction of time and the reduction of what he calls the realm of necessity to open up the realm of freedom will be the sort of basis of historical development after capitalism.

54:18.400 --> 54:21.400
And I just don't think that's true.

54:21.400 --> 54:30.400
And I think that that's only one of many goods that people might choose to sort of spend less time.

54:30.400 --> 54:44.400
But I think the value that people place in their activity will mean that it will almost be impossible to tell whether something is labor saving or not, and even to distinguish between what is necessary and what is free.

54:44.400 --> 54:50.400
So I don't think that one can develop a law of motion as one has a law of motion for capitalism.

54:50.400 --> 55:06.400
I think that when we think of this as the true beginning of history, it means that there are actually thousands if not millions of possible paths humanity might take on the basis of those fundamental principles.

55:06.400 --> 55:15.400
And it's not really necessary for us to determine which of those is taken only to kind of set us on that road.

55:15.400 --> 55:22.400
And to me that's what's actually incredibly moving about the concept of communism is that I have no idea.

55:22.400 --> 55:29.400
And that's because we inherit certain kinds of technological and social and natural conditions.

55:29.400 --> 55:40.400
And the communism that emerges this decade is going to be very different than the one that could have emerged 40 years ago, if we think it could have.

55:40.400 --> 55:54.400
And there's not just one if we really look if we really think of it as if we're really materialists and we really think of it as having is emerging from particular historical conditions that is going to have particular character.

55:54.400 --> 56:07.400
And, you know, and then and then it will open up onto a horizon that in some sense, you know, probably largely undetermined.

56:07.400 --> 56:13.400
I mean, will people and which has to do with questions of human nature, you know, which humans will humans want to go to the stars?

56:13.400 --> 56:20.400
Will they just, you know, forget language and become, you know, who knows?

56:20.400 --> 56:22.400
It's really hard to say, right?

56:22.400 --> 56:34.400
We'd have to know what humans are, and we can't really know that until we produce a society that's based on their cultivation and development and harmony with all other life.

56:34.400 --> 56:53.400
Oh, it's so super hard for me because I'm absolutely split between loving the idea because of its openness, because of its kind of inherent optimism in the sense of deep affection for humans as such, I'd say.

56:53.400 --> 57:13.400
But also there's a part in me which thinks that there has to be a somewhat pragmatic approach towards it as well, not in the sense of like limiting these types of imaginations, but making them plausible for a larger number of people.

57:13.400 --> 57:18.400
And this is not only done on the level of affection.

57:18.400 --> 57:43.400
It is at the end, I would agree it is mostly, but there's also a different layer to it where if you want to have like large masses of people join in in this idea of a super emphatic proceduralism, then you would have to address a different layer within them as well.

57:43.400 --> 57:49.400
And it is a layer that has a need for some sort of existential security as well.

57:50.400 --> 58:13.400
And if you do dismiss this, then I think the counter argument is kind of valid that it does not recognize the people that you want to persuade in all of the complexity, which includes the anxieties of societies today, the need for existential security.

58:13.400 --> 58:24.400
Because it's a very, very strong leap into the open that you argue for. And I love it, but it's a lot to ask.

58:24.400 --> 58:42.400
Absolutely, absolutely. And we need to understand why people don't make that leap and the kind of fears that they have and the reasons why they never would on the basis of ideas or persuasion or hope.

58:42.400 --> 58:57.400
And I agree, people want security. Revolutions often fail because people value their own security above all else and they're willing to accept whatever consequences for the return of that.

58:57.400 --> 59:07.400
And so any conception of revolution really has to understand, be able to think something about revolutionary motives.

59:07.400 --> 59:17.400
But I also think that revolution won't be a matter of persuasion in the sense that we're convincing people to do something and then they do it. That's not how revolution comes about.

59:17.400 --> 59:28.400
And people who don't know they're making communism can nonetheless make it. So when it comes to talking about giving people security, I think we're not talking about persuading them to think one thing.

59:28.400 --> 59:40.400
We're talking about producing conditions that people will actually fight for, that improve their lives. And real security, that would be the basis and that can't be dispossessed.

59:40.400 --> 59:52.400
And that then becomes the basis on which they make communism, not we persuade them into doing it. And so that's, I think, just a very different way of conceiving of...

59:52.400 --> 01:00:02.400
And I think the persuasion is a part of it now for us as writers, in a sense, and that's not, you know, and as people within the communist movement.

01:00:02.400 --> 01:00:17.400
But what we're doing now is, of course, very different than the kind of practical work that will be a matter of pragmatics, of course, and trial and error and the criticism of history itself.

01:00:17.400 --> 01:00:31.400
And it will be very, you know, and we don't have to figure it all out now. What we can do, I think, is, you know, begin to think about what it looks like and think of it in material terms.

01:00:31.400 --> 01:00:46.400
So I've tried to be more... I think I'm trying to be very practical in the way that I... I'm trying to talk very specifically about what it would look like, but it's hard, I guess, under the conditions I've set myself.

01:00:46.400 --> 01:01:05.400
And I often feel like, you know, I should put a bag over my head because I talk about communism with such incredible earnestness. I'm trying to... I'm willing to embarrass myself to try to, you know, share some sense that it's possible with people, which is, you know, which I believe.

01:01:05.400 --> 01:01:18.400
And I do think that that is important, and we need a positive vision. At the same time, you know, we... I, you know, I don't think that we can give people a blueprint.

01:01:18.400 --> 01:01:26.400
And I also don't know that a blueprint itself would be what's most convincing, right? I don't think that, you know...

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:40.400
Saros, you know, for all its merits. I don't know, it's not going to convince it. Well, maybe it will, but it convinces a particular kind of person, you know, who may be important, but not certainly not the center of who you would need to convince, right?

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:43.400
Maybe get some engineers on our side. It's important.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:47.400
Yeah, they are super important, I think. Super duper important.

01:01:47.400 --> 01:01:49.400
Yeah, we need the engineers. That's true.

01:01:49.400 --> 01:02:06.400
I mean, you touched upon it multiple times within the interview already, but maybe you could share your thoughts on this question of transformation a bit more. You talk about revolution. What is it that you mean with revolution, actually?

01:02:06.400 --> 01:02:17.400
Well, I simply can't imagine any meaningful move away from capitalism happening except in a moment of the breakdown of capitalist social relations.

01:02:17.400 --> 01:02:31.400
And that could be introduced by, you know, direct class struggle or by something else, but it would have to become an active interruption of capitalist reproduction by people trying to produce something else.

01:02:31.400 --> 01:02:44.400
And of course, the only people who would do that are any massive numbers of the people who've been dispossessed by capitalism is certainly not going to happen from the people who stand to benefit from the current system.

01:02:44.400 --> 01:03:01.400
So that's how I imagine revolution is the great majority, you know, taking control of their own lives in a condition where capitalist reproduction is interrupted.

01:03:01.400 --> 01:03:05.400
It's hard to imagine it happening in some other situation.

01:03:05.400 --> 01:03:19.400
But sometimes, you know, progressions of capitalism through struggle can introduce that kind of interruption. There are many types of interruption crisis, but revolution always emerges as a consequence of crisis in some way.

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:33.400
And so that's the opening that, you know, millions of people will or won't seize.

01:03:33.400 --> 01:03:41.400
And I think that's the only basis on which we could hope for a real transformation of society.

01:03:42.400 --> 01:03:55.400
All of the organizational things that people do within capitalism don't seem to move it and actually end up often being kind of stabilizing for it.

01:03:55.400 --> 01:04:03.400
The good news is that there are lots of crazies and things are getting worse for capitalism.

01:04:03.400 --> 01:04:09.400
And so, you know, it looks like we may get some chances.

01:04:09.400 --> 01:04:14.400
This would be a like a violent upheaval in some sort.

01:04:14.400 --> 01:04:18.400
You know, I don't know. I don't think it necessarily has to be violent.

01:04:18.400 --> 01:04:29.400
I think that it's hard to imagine there wouldn't necessarily be violence involved, but it doesn't necessarily have to be punctual.

01:04:29.400 --> 01:04:38.400
You know, insurrection is probably the basis on which revolution would happen, but insurrection is not revolution itself.

01:04:38.400 --> 01:04:43.400
And revolutions can be kind of protracted. They can involve periods of struggle.

01:04:43.400 --> 01:04:47.400
It's hard to imagine that violence won't be a part of it.

01:04:47.400 --> 01:04:53.400
Unfortunately, you know, violence and class struggle are just part of it, are together.

01:04:53.400 --> 01:05:02.400
But I think that, yeah, many of the ways that we conceive of revolution as a kind of war of class against class is probably not no longer applicable.

01:05:02.400 --> 01:05:10.400
And the mechanisms of violence are so strong right now, you know, that revolution as total war is sort of unimaginable.

01:05:10.400 --> 01:05:25.400
At the same time, you know, one will not overcome the power of the state and the police probably through, you know, through words.

01:05:25.400 --> 01:05:39.400
Well, no, not through words, but I do kind of favor a conception of revolution that is not so much tied to this like one decisive moment of upheaval or insurrection,

01:05:39.400 --> 01:05:44.400
but that kind of conceptualizes it a bit more procedural, actually.

01:05:44.400 --> 01:05:55.400
And I'm quite surprised, actually, that while you argue for a procedural type of thinking,

01:05:55.400 --> 01:06:07.400
so much with regard to how you would conceive of communism as such that you still attach yourself to this like clear cut.

01:06:07.400 --> 01:06:16.400
I mean, I'm of course being kind of a bit polemic, but kind of a clear cut moment of insurrection or upheaval

01:06:16.400 --> 01:06:33.400
because I always had the feeling as if this produces a grain of violence within the revolution as such that then kind of

01:06:33.400 --> 01:06:42.400
sours its core, so to speak, and that an idea of revolution as procedure is more attractive to me.

01:06:42.400 --> 01:06:48.400
I'm not able to put together my thoughts in English about this sufficiently, I think.

01:06:48.400 --> 01:06:58.400
But one of my guests, Iffa von Riedeker, she wrote a book about it where she talks about revolution as a interstitial meta lepsis is what she calls it,

01:06:58.400 --> 01:07:15.400
where you point towards these already like futuro modes of alternative belonging and practice that is already being practiced in the rooms in between

01:07:15.400 --> 01:07:26.400
and that those need to be fostered somehow and brought to a point where you make this the dominant paradigm as such.

01:07:26.400 --> 01:07:34.400
So this is, I mean, very crudely described by me, a type of procedural thinking about revolution as such,

01:07:34.400 --> 01:07:40.400
which I think would be quite compatible with your idea of procedural communism, actually.

01:07:40.400 --> 01:07:49.400
I do think it's a procedure. I do think that it moves and requires moments of positivity.

01:07:49.400 --> 01:07:55.400
It's not simply about blowing things up and shooting and destroying the state.

01:07:55.400 --> 01:08:02.400
The revolution, that's why I say communism is produced immediately.

