It's these kinds of positive acts of producing forms of kind of free association, people producing communism within the revolution,

01:08:11.400 --> 01:08:15.400
which is a positive thing and has to do with the positive forms of life that they're making.

01:08:15.400 --> 01:08:20.400
That's how it succeeds, not by winning the war.

01:08:20.400 --> 01:08:24.400
And if violence is a part of it, then sure.

01:08:24.400 --> 01:08:29.400
But it's not, you know, it's not most conceptions of revolution are sort of imagining, you know,

01:08:29.400 --> 01:08:35.400
first we defeat the state and we keep all of this kind of economic machinery in place and then we'll change that.

01:08:35.400 --> 01:08:44.400
I think that's wrong. You defeat the state by undoing the very base, the very infrastructure of capitalism.

01:08:44.400 --> 01:08:56.400
And so, you know, I agree, it is positive and it's likely to be protracted and not, you know, something that happens in a single period.

01:08:56.400 --> 01:09:04.400
And also the thing that needs to be said is any revolution we've seen emerges from a crisis and there's an insurrection,

01:09:04.400 --> 01:09:09.400
various parties are in power, there's a kind of splitting, there's kind of bifurcation of power.

01:09:09.400 --> 01:09:11.400
So it's not going to be one thing.

01:09:11.400 --> 01:09:21.400
Of course, there will be moments of interregnum where, you know, various people try to restore class society in various kinds of forms

01:09:21.400 --> 01:09:23.400
and other people are trying to push it forward.

01:09:23.400 --> 01:09:25.400
That's, in fact, what we can expect.

01:09:25.400 --> 01:09:32.400
And it's in that situation of kind of partial revolution that these questions will really be pertinent.

01:09:32.400 --> 01:09:37.400
And it is absolutely about producing kind of positivity in that moment.

01:09:37.400 --> 01:09:44.400
That it's not simply about going around and shooting all the capitalists or, you know, or that.

01:09:44.400 --> 01:09:52.400
But also those things will happen, too, because that's the kind of nature of sort of class struggle.

01:09:52.400 --> 01:09:56.400
But you can't, you know, win by that alone.

01:09:56.400 --> 01:10:08.400
And so, yeah, I mean, once you start to think about these things as in some sense out of anyone's control, it begins to look pretty different.

01:10:08.400 --> 01:10:17.400
So, you know, I think that there's much to be said for this, you know, vision of it as a protracted process.

01:10:17.400 --> 01:10:25.400
At the same time, we don't see within capitalism the emergence of any of these new forms of life that are actually leading.

01:10:25.400 --> 01:10:31.400
If we talk about laws of motion that lead towards that, they lead back into capitalism, always and in every time.

01:10:31.400 --> 01:10:39.400
And the only instances of something promising that I can find are in these moments of insurrection or rupture.

01:10:39.400 --> 01:10:46.400
You know, whether it's Italy in the 70s or Argentina or, you know, Spanish Civil War.

01:10:46.400 --> 01:10:49.400
It's hard to imagine it happening.

01:10:49.400 --> 01:10:57.400
But, you know, that doesn't mean that it's going to look like it did in the past.

01:10:57.400 --> 01:11:01.400
That's interesting. I'm quite sure that this is a question of how you look at it.

01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:12.400
I think that the temporality is something that might be of importance here, because I guess if you think of revolution as a more procedural type of thing,

01:11:12.400 --> 01:11:32.400
then the idea that communism will come into being immediately within the revolution is already a temporality that is wrong in the sense of it will have to already have existed at this moment.

01:11:32.400 --> 01:11:38.400
Unless this wasn't the case, then it won't be able to come about.

01:11:38.400 --> 01:11:49.400
I think that's the different temporality that the communism that will come about is already here, but only like in part.

01:11:49.400 --> 01:11:55.400
So I'm quite sure that this decisive break kind of idea doesn't really work,

01:11:55.400 --> 01:12:04.400
because this reminds me actually of the approach that Seros puts forward with this kind of nudging and mechanism, this design type of thinking.

01:12:04.400 --> 01:12:11.400
This is also an idea where the other is coming into society from the outside,

01:12:11.400 --> 01:12:18.400
and it will have to rely on nudging and stuff like that in order to work, because people are kind of not yet ready.

01:12:18.400 --> 01:12:21.400
And we both disagree with this kind of notion.

01:12:21.400 --> 01:12:44.400
But I'm wondering how this idea of revolution that is this kind of clear-cut type of thing isn't more or less duplicating this type of externality within a certain type of temporality when thinking about revolution, actually.

01:12:45.400 --> 01:12:58.400
Well, I don't think it does, but I think one would require a conception of the communist measure or the communist act that could produce communism as action.

01:12:58.400 --> 01:13:04.400
And one would have to imagine who would do that.

01:13:04.400 --> 01:13:18.400
But I think it's fairly easy to imagine self-organizing groups of proletarians producing communism for their own benefit and then also then benefiting others who then continue to produce it and it reproduces itself.

01:13:18.400 --> 01:13:25.400
So the idea is that there's a kind of concatenation of communist measures and communist acts that kind of link together.

01:13:25.400 --> 01:13:38.400
And a few of them on their own wouldn't produce communism, but if you link them together enough in the process of revolution, you get something that looks like communism appearing.

01:13:38.400 --> 01:13:45.400
In that sense, it makes sense to say it is emerging immediately, but nonetheless still being transitional.

01:13:45.400 --> 01:13:57.400
So that's sort of how I conceive of it. And of course, I conceive of it emerging in a situation where the debates we're having right now are appearing in some transformed form.

01:13:57.400 --> 01:14:08.400
And, you know, it's to say the class society is broken down and its future is uncertain and various parties are trying to shape the way it goes.

01:14:08.400 --> 01:14:23.400
And so there will be people trying different kinds of things, but that's the context in which I imagine this process of communization occurring as a sort of revolution within a revolution in a moment of uncertainty.

01:14:23.400 --> 01:14:30.400
And so, you know, that could be protracted. It could be there's all kinds of ways that it might look nothing like what we've seen in the past.

01:14:30.400 --> 01:14:39.400
But nonetheless, I think that's the only basis on which one can imagine getting out of this terrible bind we're in.

01:14:39.400 --> 01:14:51.400
But what's the time scale then? Because I mean, I feel it's much easier to agree with this generosity that you give, you know, towards the process as well.

01:14:51.400 --> 01:15:01.400
If I think of, all right, OK, in the time scale of like maybe thousands of years or hundreds of years, like 800 years, OK, maybe.

01:15:02.400 --> 01:15:05.400
Well, I mean, look at what's happening. Look at what's coming.

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:11.400
I think you're going to see a massive crisis that we don't have 100 years.

01:15:11.400 --> 01:15:19.400
We have in 10 years, we are going to begin to see consequences that capitalism cannot address, cannot ameliorate and mitigate.

01:15:19.400 --> 01:15:27.400
And I don't know what that is going to produce, but it's going to it's we don't have 80 years.

01:15:27.400 --> 01:15:30.400
And I think that things are going to look very different in 15 years.

01:15:30.400 --> 01:15:36.400
I mean, I could be completely wrong. But my guess is that capitalism has no way of addressing this.

01:15:36.400 --> 01:15:49.400
And, you know, I think that people will realize that the total transformation of the system is the only way to to protect their basic dignity and life and health and that various, you know, attempts to reckon with that will be made.

01:15:49.400 --> 01:15:51.400
That's that's my hope, you know.

01:15:51.400 --> 01:15:59.400
And it's all right. I mean, and already we see and this is why I think, you know, I mean, just looking at the past 10 years, where have we seen class struggle?

01:15:59.400 --> 01:16:02.400
Where that's that's hopeful or emancipatory.

01:16:02.400 --> 01:16:06.400
It's almost always emerged in response to some crisis.

01:16:06.400 --> 01:16:15.400
Right. And and, you know, we think about the wave around, you know, the wave of struggle from 2010 to 2012.

01:16:15.400 --> 01:16:28.400
And so, you know, there's a market relationship to the 2008 crisis that, you know, the George Floyd uprising in the United States clearly emerges from a particular kind of crisis condition.

01:16:28.400 --> 01:16:35.400
You know, the Julie Jean movement articulates itself in relationship to a particular kind of crisis.

01:16:36.400 --> 01:16:41.400
And that's just the beginning of these like gas price riots all over the world.

01:16:41.400 --> 01:16:48.400
So I just think that we have plenty of confirmation that that's where class struggle comes from, you know, in a loose and undetermined way.

01:16:48.400 --> 01:16:52.400
And these but these crises are are are converging.

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:59.400
And, of course, in response to that, people like you are having conversations about how do we what kinds of reforms can we make now?

01:16:59.400 --> 01:17:02.400
What can we do now? Does it have to be a revolution?

01:17:02.400 --> 01:17:03.400
That doesn't make sense.

01:17:03.400 --> 01:17:07.400
And people are organizing and beginning to kind of engage in class struggle.

01:17:07.400 --> 01:17:09.400
All of that is part of it. Right.

01:17:09.400 --> 01:17:21.400
You can't separate the can't separate these punctual moments of class struggle from, you know, all of the conversations that are happening and all the different other kinds of forms of struggle.

01:17:21.400 --> 01:17:28.400
So, you know, that that's that's that's I think the horizon.

01:17:28.400 --> 01:17:30.400
I don't know. I don't know if it's hopeful.

01:17:30.400 --> 01:17:32.400
I mean, it's the only story I believe in.

01:17:32.400 --> 01:17:34.400
Yeah, I wish I wish we had an easier way.

01:17:34.400 --> 01:17:47.400
I wish we could just, you know, write a bunch of smart articles and then everybody would do stuff differently or just, you know, have a conversation and agree on the obvious way to do things and just do it.

01:17:47.400 --> 01:17:56.400
You know, that's definitely not going to work because of what you rightly pointed out is that it's not us telling the others how to do it.

01:17:56.400 --> 01:17:58.400
But there needs to be a different practice.

01:17:58.400 --> 01:17:59.400
Right.

01:17:59.400 --> 01:18:19.400
I'm not sure if this different practice is brought about through this the specific types of revolutionary processes that you describe, because they they are also a very, very, very smart way for the for the powers to be to to learn very effectively.

01:18:19.400 --> 01:18:41.400
The way that the that the like central banks and and the players that that needed to respond within the pandemic in the West Western world and the way in which they were able to get back to a certain type of knowledge that they accumulated after the 2008-2009 financial crisis.

01:18:41.400 --> 01:18:53.400
This was a really, really quick moment of reaction within systemic players that that could could utilize this knowledge.

01:18:53.400 --> 01:19:00.400
And so there is a like process of learning from from these crisis and adapting to them.

01:19:00.400 --> 01:19:15.400
And I mean, if you look at the way the central banks is is making politics, this does not match any form of neoliberalism that you could get out of any book.

01:19:15.400 --> 01:19:17.400
You know, it doesn't it just doesn't fit.

01:19:17.400 --> 01:19:25.400
It's already something different and it already transformed like essential in in essential modes of governing.

01:19:25.400 --> 01:19:36.400
And this is this is this is kind of super frightening because it's it's it points towards a high, very high degree of adaptability.

01:19:36.400 --> 01:19:44.400
Absolutely. I agree. I agree. And I pay attention to these developments with great interest and great surprise and alarm.

01:19:44.400 --> 01:19:55.400
I must say that, you know, I didn't really believe in those that state had such capacities, you know, 10 years ago when I was much more pessimistic about its intervention.

01:19:55.400 --> 01:20:01.400
So, yeah, we have to really learn from these things. And of course, yeah, crises often just make capital stronger.

01:20:01.400 --> 01:20:07.400
Nonetheless, this is the only place where I see, you know, class struggle that could be the basis for this.

01:20:07.400 --> 01:20:17.400
I see people trying to make their own lives, you know, engaging in in, you know, free, transparent activity on the basis of equality.

01:20:17.400 --> 01:20:21.400
That's the only place I've ever seen it in the world is in these moments of struggle.

01:20:21.400 --> 01:20:30.400
I don't, you know, because everywhere else is just foreclosed by the commodity form or, you know, various kinds of divisions.

01:20:30.400 --> 01:20:38.400
And I just think, you know, that that's our hope is to kind of expand, expand those moments.

01:20:38.400 --> 01:20:45.400
I don't even know if I could say it's likely, but I think that it's, you know, I don't know. Everything else looks horrible.

01:20:45.400 --> 01:20:46.400
That's all I can say.

01:20:46.400 --> 01:20:52.400
And what would you say? How big of a crisis are we heading towards?

01:20:52.400 --> 01:20:56.400
Because you seem to think that this is kind of a precondition.

01:20:56.400 --> 01:21:03.400
How would you analyze the current state of affairs in that regard?

01:21:03.400 --> 01:21:09.400
Well, I think that that crisis is both punctual and ongoing, and there's different kinds of crises.

01:21:09.400 --> 01:21:18.400
There's kind of ongoing crisis of capitalism that, you know, we can date as going back to the 70s or we could date it going back to 2008.

01:21:18.400 --> 01:21:26.400
But this kind of protracted crisis and that produces is already producing forms of class struggle that we can see.

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:31.400
And then there's these kind of punctual crises, for instance, as we've just passed through.

01:21:32.400 --> 01:21:43.400
And so, you know, what will remote the destabilization is most likely to emerge from kind of overlapping crises.

01:21:43.400 --> 01:21:57.400
And so, you know, everything I can see just points to the intensification of these crises that emerge from fundamental contradictions of capitalism.

01:21:57.400 --> 01:22:07.400
But also we, you know, a huge environmental crisis is about to descend upon us is already descending upon us.

01:22:07.400 --> 01:22:13.400
And I have no idea what kinds of what what the, you know, forms of class struggle might emerge.

01:22:13.400 --> 01:22:17.400
And in the context of that remains a very much an open question.

01:22:17.400 --> 01:22:23.400
But I remain quite certain that it will produce forms of class struggle.

01:22:23.400 --> 01:22:44.400
So I think that that, you know, I guess I would say that that my sense is that there's some possible convergence of these crises in in various places that might be the opening for for a transition away from capitalism and class society.

01:22:44.400 --> 01:23:02.400
